            <!-- Contents -->
            <noteGrp type="workDesc">
               <note type="description">Treatise on the symbolism of the letter bāʾ, the first
                     manifestation of being and the intermediary between the One and the many. Ibn
                     ‘Arabi says in his preface that he wrote it at the request of one of his
                     disciples, who had asked him to write a work on the Divine Realities, based on
                     a spiritual address he had received regarding the bāʾ.</note>
               <note type="structure"/>
               <note type="contentsNote"/>
            </noteGrp>
            <!-- Stemmatics -->
            <note type="stemmatics">A much copied work, verified by at least four historic mss.
                  The best is the holograph Yusuf Aga 4868 (undated). The second is Veliyuddin 51,
                  dated 762H, copied from an original in the hand of the author, possibly YA 4868?
                  According to OY, the work was written in 602H in Jerusalem on the basis of a note
                  on Veliyuddin 51, but our investigation shows that no place or date is given. (See
                  Jane Clark and Denis McAuley Some Notes on the Manuscript Veliyyudin 51, JMIAS 40,
                  2006.)</note>
